for reference, "The "Martian
is 100,000 words, 105,000.

00:50:15.740 --> 00:50:17.680
So I got about 70,000
words into "Zhek"

00:50:17.680 --> 00:50:18.920
over the course of a year.

00:50:18.920 --> 00:50:22.660
And I realized one day, I'm
like, oh dear, this sucks.

00:50:22.660 --> 00:50:25.240
And I told my
editor, I'm like, I'm

00:50:25.240 --> 00:50:27.802
concerned that "Zhek" sucks.

00:50:27.802 --> 00:50:30.010
Would it be OK if I wrote
a completely different book

00:50:30.010 --> 00:50:31.840
and you added a
year to my deadline?

00:50:31.840 --> 00:50:33.145
And he said, sure, go ahead.

00:50:33.145 --> 00:50:35.020
Because he'd been reading
the chapters and he

00:50:35.020 --> 00:50:36.360
also knew that "Zhek" sucked.

00:50:36.360 --> 00:50:36.860
So--

00:50:36.860 --> 00:50:38.605
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:38.605 --> 00:50:40.480
--he was actually very
comfortable with that.

00:50:40.480 --> 00:50:44.240
But while I was bungling
around trying to fix "Zhek"--

00:50:44.240 --> 00:50:44.740
and I did.

00:50:44.740 --> 00:50:47.410
I spent a lot of time trying
to make it work as a story--

00:50:47.410 --> 00:50:50.560
I was also cheating on it
by going over and working

00:50:50.560 --> 00:50:51.370
on "Artemis."

00:50:51.370 --> 00:50:53.530
So it's hard for me to
give a quantitative answer

00:50:53.530 --> 00:50:56.380
because I kind of split my time.

00:50:56.380 --> 00:51:00.250
AUDIENCE: So the question
I had was about the film

00:51:00.250 --> 00:51:03.315
adaptation and what--

00:51:03.315 --> 00:51:04.940
you've probably been
asked this before,

00:51:04.940 --> 00:51:07.000
but what are your just
general thoughts on that?

00:51:07.000 --> 00:51:10.360
And also, I'm curious
kind of how they reach out

00:51:10.360 --> 00:51:12.790
to you on that,
and wanting to turn

00:51:12.790 --> 00:51:15.130
the book into a movie,
and kind of the process

00:51:15.130 --> 00:51:16.660
of that happening.

00:51:16.660 --> 00:51:19.030
ANDY WEIR: They send a
jewel-encrusted helicopter.

00:51:19.030 --> 00:51:20.110
No.

00:51:20.110 --> 00:51:23.350
So what happened was, while we
were negotiating the book deal

00:51:23.350 --> 00:51:26.780
with Random House, Fox wanted
the film rights, right then.

00:51:26.780 --> 00:51:29.140
Like they came-- like it was
still just a self-published

00:51:29.140 --> 00:51:31.690
book on Amazon when Fox--

00:51:31.690 --> 00:51:33.550
for those of you who
don't understand,

00:51:33.550 --> 00:51:36.250
the way movie options
work, is what they're doing

00:51:36.250 --> 00:51:38.230
is they're paying you
a small amount of money

00:51:38.230 --> 00:51:42.110
to have the exclusive ability
to buy the film rights from you.

00:51:42.110 --> 00:51:44.313
So it's not like you're
just rolling in money

00:51:44.313 --> 00:51:45.730
and they're going
to make a movie.

00:51:45.730 --> 00:51:48.160
It's like, we may or may
not want to make a movie out

00:51:48.160 --> 00:51:50.770
of this, but we're going
to secure it by giving you

00:51:50.770 --> 00:51:52.000
a small amount of money.

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:54.580
You pre-negotiate the entire
contract, the whole purchase

00:51:54.580 --> 00:51:56.080
contract in advance.

00:51:56.080 --> 00:51:58.205
And we're going to give
you a small amount of money

00:51:58.205 --> 00:52:00.730
to be the only people who can
buy the rights for the next,

00:52:00.730 --> 00:52:01.690
like, 18 months.

00:52:01.690 --> 00:52:02.590
It expires.

00:52:02.590 --> 00:52:04.323
And we can buy the
rights at any time

00:52:04.323 --> 00:52:06.490
just by activating this
contract and then giving you

00:52:06.490 --> 00:52:09.050
the big pile of money.

00:52:09.050 --> 00:52:10.990
So when they came
for the film option,

00:52:10.990 --> 00:52:12.880
it wasn't that
big of a surprise.

00:52:12.880 --> 00:52:15.250
Movie studios buy film option--
they'll throw those out

00:52:15.250 --> 00:52:17.140
and they're like
breath mints to them.

00:52:17.140 --> 00:52:19.515
I mean, it's a lot of money
to me, but to them it's like,

00:52:19.515 --> 00:52:20.530
pfft, here.

00:52:20.530 --> 00:52:21.950
Go buy yourself
something pretty.

00:52:21.950 --> 00:52:23.833
You know.

00:52:23.833 --> 00:52:25.000
But they bought film rights.

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:27.560
And so those two deals were
going on at the same time.

00:52:27.560 --> 00:52:29.018
And the book deal
and the film deal

00:52:29.018 --> 00:52:30.490
came together four days apart.

00:52:30.490 --> 00:52:32.532
And that was a-- you know,
and I was, by the way,

00:52:32.532 --> 00:52:33.970
still working as an engineer.

00:52:33.970 --> 00:52:35.380
So I'm in my
cubicle fixing bugs,

00:52:35.380 --> 00:52:36.820
then running off to
a conference room,

00:52:36.820 --> 00:52:38.570
take a call about my
movie deal, then back

00:52:38.570 --> 00:52:39.930
to my cubicle to fix bugs.

00:52:39.930 --> 00:52:41.470
It was a surreal time.

00:52:41.470 --> 00:52:44.600
But anyway, as the
movie progressed--

00:52:44.600 --> 00:52:47.470
there's never a moment
when you pop the champagne.

00:52:47.470 --> 00:52:48.670
It's just bit by bit.

00:52:48.670 --> 00:52:50.380
They're like, oh, we got a guy.

00:52:50.380 --> 00:52:53.530
We've got a potential
screenwriter.

00:52:53.530 --> 00:52:55.120
So we're going
to-- you know, he's

00:52:55.120 --> 00:52:56.412
going to start working on that.

00:52:56.412 --> 00:52:56.920
Oh, OK.

00:52:56.920 --> 00:52:57.647
We think we may--

00:52:57.647 --> 00:52:59.105
we've got a pretty
good screenplay.

00:52:59.105 --> 00:53:00.860
The studio is like,
well, we're not--

00:53:00.860 --> 00:53:03.640
it's so heavily dependent
on one character

00:53:03.640 --> 00:53:06.070
that we're not going to
make it at all unless you

00:53:06.070 --> 00:53:08.122
can get a big name
to play that one guy.

00:53:08.122 --> 00:53:10.330
And it's like, OK, we pitched
it to Robert Downey Jr.

00:53:10.330 --> 00:53:11.830
and he said no.

00:53:11.830 --> 00:53:15.518
And then, so then
they're, we're going

00:53:15.518 --> 00:53:17.560
to pitch it to Matt Damon
next, see what he says.

00:53:17.560 --> 00:53:18.622
Matt Damon said yes.

00:53:18.622 --> 00:53:19.330
I was like, what?

00:53:19.330 --> 00:53:22.228
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:23.560 --> 00:53:26.350
And then they had Drew
Goddard lined up to direct,

00:53:26.350 --> 00:53:30.310
but then he left to go work
on Sony's next "Marvel" movie.

00:53:30.310 --> 00:53:32.390
And so then they're
like, OK, well,

00:53:32.390 --> 00:53:34.870
we've got Matt Damon interested,
but we need a director.

00:53:34.870 --> 00:53:36.590
And then Ridley Scott said yes.

00:53:36.590 --> 00:53:37.907
And I said, what?

00:53:37.907 --> 00:53:40.490
And so then the studio started
to-- and it starts to snowball,

00:53:40.490 --> 00:53:41.890
but there's never a moment.

00:53:41.890 --> 00:53:44.110
And they're like, OK, well,
they're talking about,

00:53:44.110 --> 00:53:45.640
they're doing some
concept sketches.

00:53:45.640 --> 00:53:47.580
OK, well, Ridley's
meeting with that.

00:53:47.580 --> 00:53:50.128
OK, well, now
Jessica Chastain is

00:53:50.128 --> 00:53:51.670
interested in playing
Commander Lewis

00:53:51.670 --> 00:53:54.128
and we're starting to get a
cast together, but none of this

00:53:54.128 --> 00:53:56.332
means that we're actually
going to make the movie.

00:53:56.332 --> 00:53:57.790
And then, OK, well,
eventually it's

00:53:57.790 --> 00:54:01.990
like, well, we've leased some
studio space in Budapest.

00:54:01.990 --> 00:54:04.157
It's like, OK, well,
we're making sets now.

00:54:04.157 --> 00:54:05.740
I'm like, well,
that's good, isn't it?

00:54:05.740 --> 00:54:07.532
Yeah, but it doesn't
always, eh, you know--

00:54:07.532 --> 00:54:08.950
[LAUGHTER]

00:54:08.950 --> 00:54:11.800
And then eventually they
shot the first scene.

00:54:11.800 --> 00:54:13.780
And that's when you kind
of pop the champagne.

00:54:13.780 --> 00:54:15.610
Because once they
shoot the first scene,

00:54:15.610 --> 00:54:19.060
they're on the hook to pay
all the actors all the money.

00:54:19.060 --> 00:54:21.280
And that's the expensive
part, is the salaries

00:54:21.280 --> 00:54:22.330
that the actors make.

00:54:22.330 --> 00:54:25.150
So once they shoot that
first scene, then it--

00:54:25.150 --> 00:54:27.340
even if they wanted to stop,
the cheaper thing to do

00:54:27.340 --> 00:54:30.410
is just power through and make
the movie to offset the costs.

00:54:30.410 --> 00:54:33.100
And that's when they gave me the
big pile of money, too, which

00:54:33.100 --> 00:54:33.820
was awesome.

00:54:33.820 --> 00:54:34.580
I recommend it.

00:54:34.580 --> 00:54:35.080
And--

00:54:35.080 --> 00:54:37.653
[LAUGHTER]

00:54:37.653 --> 00:54:39.820
--another thing that I get
asked a lot is, like, OK,

00:54:39.820 --> 00:54:42.280
how were you involved in the
process of making the movie?

00:54:42.280 --> 00:54:44.870
My job was to cash the check.

00:54:44.870 --> 00:54:45.370
That's it.

00:54:45.370 --> 00:54:47.927
Like, once you yield the--
once you sell the film rights,

00:54:47.927 --> 00:54:49.510
they don't have to
talk to you at all.

00:54:49.510 --> 00:54:52.450
They chose to include me,
though, which was pretty cool.

00:54:52.450 --> 00:54:54.050
When Drew was writing
the screenplay,

00:54:54.050 --> 00:54:55.840
he was on the phone
with me every day,

00:54:55.840 --> 00:54:57.850
usually with
technical questions,

00:54:57.850 --> 00:54:59.860
although sometimes
the story questions.

00:54:59.860 --> 00:55:02.155
Ridley would also--
it took me a long time

00:55:02.155 --> 00:55:04.780
to get used to the fact, by the
way, that in Hollywood everyone

00:55:04.780 --> 00:55:06.610
calls each other by first names.

00:55:06.610 --> 00:55:08.932
And so I'm like, man,
everybody's such a douche.

00:55:08.932 --> 00:55:11.140
They're talking about these
incredibly famous people,

00:55:11.140 --> 00:55:12.765
and they're like,
oh, Matt, oh, Ridley.

00:55:12.765 --> 00:55:15.400
And then after like two
weeks in that environment,

00:55:15.400 --> 00:55:16.337
you're doing it too.

00:55:16.337 --> 00:55:17.920
So pardon me if I
sound like a douche,

00:55:17.920 --> 00:55:20.170
but this is just how they do it.

00:55:20.170 --> 00:55:23.980
So Ridley Scott
would be calling me,

00:55:23.980 --> 00:55:26.500
sending questions
through intermediaries

00:55:26.500 --> 00:55:28.213
with technical stuff.

00:55:28.213 --> 00:55:30.130
But for the most part,
they certainly didn't--

00:55:30.130 --> 00:55:31.960
I had no authority whatsoever.

00:55:31.960 --> 00:55:33.590
And I had no say over anything.

00:55:33.590 --> 00:55:35.590
But I'm very happy
with how it turned out.

00:55:35.590 --> 00:55:37.410
As excited spectator
on the sidelines.

00:55:37.410 --> 00:55:38.170
Yay!

00:55:38.170 --> 00:55:39.967
Go team!

00:55:39.967 --> 00:55:41.050
JASON GESSNER: Well, cool.

00:55:41.050 --> 00:55:45.780
So everybody, let's give a big
round of applause for Andy.

00:55:45.780 --> 00:55:48.830
[APPLAUSE]

